- Active alerts are those with a status of 'active';
- The air quality data includes temperature and height above ground;
- The user information includes the full name of the person assigned to handle the alert.

- 'Bloomed with an average temperature higher than 20 degrees Celsius' refers to the average air temperature being greater than 20 degrees Celsius;
- 'Throughout the year 2023' refers to the reference time being between '2023-01-01' and '2023-12-31';
- 'How warm did they shine' refers to the average temperature of each time series.

- 'validated' indicates that the data has been verified for accuracy;
- 'Good' performance category suggests that the data meets certain quality standards;
- The average air temperature is calculated from the `air_temperature` column in the `air_quality_data` table.

- "source" refers to the entity generating the air quality data, such as a sensor or weather station;
- "reference_time" is the timestamp when the data was recorded;
- "average temperature" is the mean air temperature over all data points for each source.

- "Performance category" refers to the classification of data points based on their performance metrics;
- "Exposure category" refers to the classification of data points based on their exposure to environmental conditions;
- "Quality code" refers to the classification of data points based on their data quality;
- "Data quality score" is a numeric value indicating the reliability of the data point.

- "Most recent snapshot" refers to the data point with the latest `reference_time` in the `air_quality_data` table;
- "Source details" include the source name, type, location, model, manufacturer, description, installation date, last maintenance date, and current status;
- "Performance category descriptions" provide a textual explanation of the performance category of the data point;
- "Exposure category descriptions" provide a textual explanation of the exposure category of the data point;
- "Quality code descriptions" provide a textual explanation of the quality code of the data point.

- 'time series' refers to a sequence of data points recorded at regular intervals over time;
- 'average air temperature' is the mean temperature over the specified period;
- 'last recorded temperature' is the most recent temperature measurement in the dataset for each time series.

- Performance metrics include the performance category and its description, the data quality score, and the validation status;
- Source details include the name, type, location, data source type, and data source format of the source;
- Access logs summarize the number of times the data was accessed, the first and last access times;
- Quality alerts summarize the number of alerts generated, the first and last alert times;
- The data points are organized by their unique identifier, `data_id`.

- 'Streams of information' refers to `time_series_name` in the `time_series` table;
- 'Sourced from specific origins' refers to `source_id` in the `data_sources` table;
- 'Categorized by their performance' refers to `performance_category` in the `performance_categories` table;
- 'Blossomed with an average air temperature warmer than 10 degrees Celsius' refers to the condition `AVG(aqd.air_temperature) > 10`;
- 'The warmth they radiate' refers to the calculated `average_temperature`.

- 'highest performance' refers to the performance category 'A';
- 'most recently validated' means the data has been recently confirmed as accurate and is marked with 'validated' status;
- 'hourly data points' refers to data collected at hourly intervals.

- 'Validated' data means the data has passed quality checks and is considered reliable;
- 'Performance category 'A'' refers to the highest or best performance category;
- 'Quality code of 'Good'' indicates that the data quality is satisfactory and meets the required standards.

- Recent data is defined as data collected within the last year from the current date;
- Performance categories, exposure categories, and quality codes are described in their respective tables;
- The query focuses on air quality data with temperatures above 25 degrees Celsius, which can be considered a threshold for high temperatures.
